quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to define a class with these attributes: age of type integer, height as a double, and name as a string.
[!raw!]
{0} Person {
  {1} age;
  {2} height;
  {3} name;
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Defining Attributes[/h1]

A class has [b]attributes [/b]and [b]methods[/b]. The attributes are basically variables within a class.
Let's create a class called [b]Vehicle[/b], with its corresponding attributes and methods. [code format="java"]public class Vehicle {
  int maxSpeed;
  int wheels;
  String color;
  double fuelCapacity;  

  void horn() {
    System.out.println("Beep!");
  }  
}[/code]
[b]maxSpeed[/b], [b]wheels[/b], [b]color[/b],[b] [/b]and [b]fuelCapacity [/b]are the attributes of our Vehicle class, and[b] horn()[/b] is the only method.
[note]You can define as many attributes and methods as necessary.[/note]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to create two objects from the class "people".
[!raw!]
people obj1 = {0} people();
{1} obj2 = new people{2};

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Creating Objects[/h1]

Next, we can create multiple objects of our [b]Vehicle [/b]class, and use the dot syntax to access their attributes and methods. [code format="java" codeId="758"]class MyClass {
  public static void main(String[ ] args) {
    Vehicle v1 = new Vehicle();
    Vehicle v2 = new Vehicle();
    v1.color = "red";
    v2.horn();
  }
}[/code]
